post_text: FOOD SERVICE CHANGES: Yesterday, the USDA extended our Seamless Summer Meal program until December 31st. This waiver will allow us to return to how we were serving meals when Covid started. ALL children from ages 1 through high school seniors can come to our school for lunches. This includes children from other schools. The child does not have to be present to receive a meal. Our lunch time stays the same but note that we will no longer be providing lunches during the evening times (4-5:30pm).

post_text: Tribe Turnout will take place August 11th for students with last names beginning A-L and August 12th for students with last names beginning M-Z. The time will be 7:30 a.m. to 1:00 p.m. and will be a drive-thru event in the staff parking lot at 8th Street & Alameda. Students must remain in vehicles to practice social distancing. Class schedules, textbook checkout, Chromebook distribution (students who need a school issued Chromebook must have a parent sign the release form), and school pictures will all be part of the event.
text: Tribe Turnout will take place August 11th for students with last names beginning A-L and August 12th for students with last names beginning M-Z. The time will be 7:30 a.m. to 1:00 p.m. and will be a drive-thru event in the staff parking lot at 8th Street & Alameda. Students must remain in vehicles to practice social distancing. Class schedules, textbook checkout, Chromebook distribution (students who need a school issued Chromebook must have a parent sign the release form), and school pictures will all be part of the event.

post_text:
Madera County Department of Public Health will be holding two Facebook Live Events this week: Tuesday, July 21st (tonight) in English and Thursday, July 23rd in Spanish. Both from 6-7pm.

Join Sara Bosse, Public Health Director and Dr. Simon Paul, Public Health Officer as they provide an update on COVID-19 and discuss important and commonly requested topics such as: exposure to COVID-19, what to do if you are sick, how to isolate and quarantine, indoor vs. outdoor events, and more! There will be a question and answer portion where participants will have the opportunity to ask COVID-19 related questions. You may also submit your questions in advance by leaving a comment on either of the event posts (English|Spanish). Please keep in mind that while every attempt will be made to answer as many question as possible, all questions may not be able to be answered during the live events.

post_text: For those students and parents waiting for Senior Grad Trip refunds, we ask for your continued patience. We paid the travel company for the trip and they in turn paid their vendors. The travel company has to get their refunds back in order to be able to process our refund, among many other schools. This is taking longer than expected, but when we do receive our refund, student refunds will be issued immediately. We thank you for your understanding and continued patience!

CUHS 2020 Yearbooks are here! If you still want to order a yearbook before graduation or your drive thru day, visit the CUHS website for information. Don't remember if you purchased a Yearbook already? Contact Mr. Galloway at yearbook@chowchillahigh.org or gallowayb@chowchillahigh.org.

Distribution Schedule:
SENIORS will receive their pre-ordered Yearbook as they exit on their Graduation day (Tuesday, May 26, Wednesday, May 27, or Thursday May 28).
JUNIORS will receive their pre-ordered Yearbook at the Yearbook Photo Station during Junior Drive Thru on Tuesday, June 2 between 9:00 a.m. and 12:00 p.m.
SOPHOMORES will receive their pre-ordered Yearbook at the Yearbook Photo Station during Sophomore Drive Thru on Wednesday, June 3 between 9:00 a.m. and 12:00 p.m.
FRESHMEN will receive their pre-ordered Yearbook at the Yearbook Photo Station during Freshman Drive Thru on Thursday, June 4 between 9:00 a.m. and 12:00 p.m.
THERE WILL BE NO SALES AT THE DISTRIBUTION POINTS. Thank you for supporting our CUHS Yearbook.

shared_text:
Chowchilla Union High School District
May 7 at 8:46 AM ·

REMINDER ON SPRING UNIFORM/EQUIPMENT DROP OFF TOMORROW from Athletic Director Weston Borba:
"Attention all CUHS Spring Sport Athletes: With the State CIF's decision to cancel all remaining spring contests, we have scheduled a Uniform/Equipment Collection event to collect all Spring Season uniforms/equipment. On Friday, May 8th, the CUHS Uniform/Equipment Collection event will take place in the parking lot behind the Varsity Baseball field on Mariposa Ave. All uniforms/equipment are to be washed and cleaned and turned in at this time. This event will start at 10:00 a.m. and end at 12:00 p.m. This will be a drive up and drop off from a vehicle window event. All student athletes and families are requested to stay in their cars for the health and safety of everyone. Thank you for your cooperation. TRIBE STRONG!!!"

post_text: Halle Freitas has been using her new 3-D printer to make approximately 1,000 ear protectors and 30 medical visor face shields. She's donated to our local pharmacy, grocery, and hardware stores, vet clinic, skilled nursing facility, and health clinics. The Freitas family mailed out hundreds to the Central Valley Medical Community and she just mailed some to the Azores Portugal. It has been a family effort as they believe people need to be kinder to one another and are putting their words into actions. THANK YOU HALLE FREITAS for being TRIBE STRONG!

San Joaquin Region FFA
April 7 at 3:22 PM ·

Rachel makes and sells goat milk soap with milk from her Alpine, Oberhasli, and LaMancha dairy goats. She has grown up in the agriculture industry and has been around animals all of her life. Rachel's interest lies in a different aspect of agriculture, which is processing the dairy goat milk she collected into soap. Her responsibilities include spending an average of 8 hours a week creating and packaging soap. She is also in charge of cold-process soap making, hot-process soap making, freezing, and packaging. She has invested in equipment, soap molds, and safety gear for every step in processing soap.

San Joaquin Region FFA
April 7 at 3:22 PM ·

Rider works for Bass 4B Ranch, a Livestock Transportation company hauling cattle for dairies and auction yards and sheep, goats, and hogs for local fairs. Rider has invested 5001 hours into Bass 4B Ranch and has made $54,970.00. His responsibilities are to assist in loading and unloading cattle along with helping keep up on vehicle maintenance. After years of working Rider has taken up a position in management helping Bass 4B Ranch plan out and decide how to execute projects the company works on along with meeting with potential customers. Rider also oversees any livestock being kept by Bass 4B Ranch and aids in any expanding plans for its livestock operations.

* Case #1 - Male, 70s, travel related, recovered
* Case #2 - Male, 30s, person to person, home isolation
* Case #3 - Female, 30s, community transmission, home isolation
* Case #4 - Male, 60s, community transmission, home isolation
* Case #5 - Female, 60s, person to person, home isolation
* Case #6 - Male, 60s, person to person, hospitalized
* Case #7 - Female, 70s, pending investigation, hospitalized
All of this information can be found at the following link:
https://www.maderacounty.com/government/public-health/health-updates/corona-virus

post_text:
Madera County Department of Public Health Reports Three New Confirmed Madera County Cases of COVID-19

Madera County Department of Public Health (MCDPH) confirmed three new Madera County cases of community acquired COVID-19. All are close contacts of the March 19th cases. MCDPH Communicable Disease Investigators worked closely with Madera County Sheriff, District Attorney, and Probation investigators to identify and trace close contacts and were successful in interviewing 147 of the identified contacts within 24 hours. All contacts were quarantined and symptomatic individuals were tested. More positive cases are anticipated in the upcoming days and weeks.

There are currently five total confirmed cases in Madera County and one recovered case of COVID-19. Three of the five cases are currently hospitalized. Case count is updated Monday – Friday by 10:00 a.m. at www.maderacounty.com/covid19.

March 13 at 5:03 PM ·

MADERA COUNTY SCHOOL CLOSURE
As Fresno and Madera Counties function in many ways as a shared population, the Madera County Health Officer, Department of Public Health, and the Superintendents of Madera County public school districts have come to consensus that it is best to close public schools in Madera County. School closure is effective immediately.

post_text: On Saturday, ten members of the CUHS Academic Decathlon team competed against six other county teams. Madera South won first place but our team did very well. In Varsity Division, Jenesis Borrego received a Bronze medal in Art and a Bronze medal in Social Science. Rajdeep Singh received a Bronze medal in Interview and a Bronze medal in Mathematics. In Scholastic Division, Madisyn Delgado received a Bronze medal in Art, a Bronze medal in Economics and a Bronze medal in Essay. Hunter McGowan received a Bronze medal in Mathematics, and a Silver medal in Language and Literature. In Honor Division, Yadira Ortiz Camacho received a Bronze medal in Economics and a Silver medal in Essay. Arely Baez received a Bronze medal in Interview. All of these students are new to Academic Decathlon and they did a great job! The team is coached by Libby Cross. GO TRIBE!!

This three-year plan, the LCAP, is written to address the needs of all of our students. We value your input and invite you to be a part of this important process. Please consider attending an LCAP stakeholder input meeting. Please view the picture with all of the meeting dates, times and locations. If you have any questions please contact Danielle Ross at rossd@chowchillahigh.org or via phone at (559) 665-1331.
